Whenever possible:

• all four options should sound reasonable
• at least three options should contain information actually mentioned
• differences between options should be subtle
• avoid keyword matching

Questions should frequently test:

• implied conclusions
• unstated assumptions
• likely consequences
• strongest evidence
• speaker credibility
• reliability of evidence
• intended audience
• reason for mentioning a detail
• best summary
• why one solution is preferred over another

If two options are both partially true, only one should answer the question completely.
Avoid options that are absolutely correct or absolutely wrong.
Prefer subtle differences in:

• scope
• timing
• emphasis
• certainty
• motivation

==================================================
QUESTION DESIGN RULES
==================================================

The correct answer should NOT be identifiable from one obvious sentence.

Instead require the test taker to:

• combine information from multiple parts of the audio
• distinguish facts from opinions
• interpret implied meaning
• identify what is NOT said directly
• recognize why a speaker says something
• identify assumptions
• compare multiple viewpoints
• notice changes in opinion
• resolve conflicting information
• ignore distracting details

At least 70% of questions should require reasoning rather than recall.

==================================================
DISTRACTOR REQUIREMENTS
==================================================

Every incorrect option must be believable.

Wrong options should be based on:

• true information mentioned in another context
• partially correct interpretation
• incorrect inference
• speaker's earlier opinion that later changed
• confusion between two similar numbers, places or dates
• cause vs result
• opposite emphasis
• exaggeration
• information from only one part of the report

Avoid:

• silly answers
• obviously unrelated answers
• options that contradict the report
• grammatical clues
• one option much longer than others

Use these distractor patterns:

✓ Earlier information before a correction
✓ Common-sense assumption
✓ True detail answering a different question
✓ Cause instead of effect
✓ Effect instead of cause
✓ Speaker A's opinion instead of final conclusion
✓ Majority opinion instead of reporter's conclusion
✓ Extreme wording
✓ Missing one important condition
✓ Correct but incomplete

